item.title: Mexican Government Moves to Tighten Grip on Electricity Market
item.description: The Mexican government moved to seize more control of the country’s electricity market, affecting dozens of renewable energy projects worth more than $6 billion.

item.title: As West Cautiously Reopens, Infection Clusters Appear in Asia
item.description: While the U.S. and other countries tentatively resumed some activity this weekend after months of coronavirus lockdowns, some Asian countries that had lifted measures battling new clusters of contagion.

item.title: Israel Swears In Fragile New Government, as Friction Looms
item.description: Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu’s new unity government was sworn in Sunday, cementing a fragile political alliance with former rival Benny Gantz to end more than one year of political stalemate.

item.title: Afghan President Agrees to Share Power With Rival
item.description: Afghanistan’s President Ashraf Ghani and his rival Abdullah Abdullah agreed to a power-sharing deal, ending a feud over a disputed election that threatened to derail U.S.-backed peace efforts.

item.title: Chinese Ambassador to Israel Found Dead in His Home
item.description: China’s ambassador to Israel was found dead Sunday in his residence north of Tel Aviv, Israeli officials said.

item.title: Fearful and Wary, Italian City Ravaged by Coronavirus Slowly Re-Emerges
item.description: Bergamo, a northern Italian city hardest-hit by the pandemic and one of the most devastated in the world, is trying to restore a sense of normalcy. “If we get this right, we can turn the extreme misfortune that put us at the center of a global health pandemic into something positive,” says the city mayor.
